00:04:14.437 --> 00:04:16.467
great success in its home market.

00:04:17.537 --> 00:04:22.657
Instead, it found early traction,
initial success, across the

00:04:22.657 --> 00:04:24.407
Pacific in the United States.

00:04:25.257 --> 00:04:31.107
And specifically, with a market of
teenage girls, who absolutely loved it.

00:04:32.417 --> 00:04:37.977
Teenage girls might love to lip-synch,
to dance and pretend to sing along

00:04:37.977 --> 00:04:42.917
with pop songs, but it’s not everyone’s
cup of tea, and there are only so

00:04:42.917 --> 00:04:44.647
many teenage girls in the world.

00:04:45.697 --> 00:04:49.467
In any case, Musical.ly
was clearly onto something.

00:04:50.617 --> 00:04:56.497
Back in China, a Beijing-based technology
company called ByteDance, was developing

00:04:56.547 --> 00:05:01.377
its own video-sharing app that was
heavily inspired by, some might even

00:05:01.377 --> 00:05:04.077
